ular chef a( the\nMission Inn, was confined to his home\na few days last week by illness. Otto\nis much improved and back at work.\nH. L. Finke, prominent livestock\nman and auctioneer of the Berthold\ncountry, was in the city Monday in\nthe interest of a membership drive for\nthe Farm Bureau.\nHarry Johnson, editor of the Her\nald-News $t Edmore, was in the city\nthe latter part of the week to attend\nto business matters and a meeting of\nthe B. P. 0. Elks.\nMrs. J. N. Chase and daughter who\nBave been guests at the home of Jud\nge and Mrs. H. W. Swenson, for the\npajst week have returned td their\nhome in Grand Forks.\nHarold Stenseth, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Herman Stenseth, has returned\nto his home on Seventh street from the\nGeneral hospital where he underwent\nan operation for appendicitis.\nMADE HAPPY\nMiss Ragna Nestegard and Alice\nHillard wer\nby being placed in\nITEMS OF INTEREST\nPERSONAL AND LOCAL MENTION\nIN AND ABOUT DEVILS LAKE\nFORECAST\nFor the Upper Mississippi\nand Lower Missouri Valleys:\nGenerally fair, with tempera\ntare normal or above.\nLocal Forecast:\u2014Clear tonight\nand probably Thursday, not\nmuch change in temperature.\nValentines\u2014Get them at Slorby A\nBerg's. cl-26\nle happy last week\npositions by Aaker*s\nCollege, Grand Forks, add\nmore to the many started on(\nto greater opportunities.-,\nYour turn will come too if yoo en-!\nroll at the_ A. B. C.\u2014position-salary\nmore do you\nFor free eat-\nind address, tear out\nValentines\u2014Get them at Slorb\u00a3 Ik\nBerg's. cl-86\nMrs. Nick Meuhlen, of Penn, visit\ned friehdB in thf.pity the latter part\nof the week. j.\nA. E. fireidert, hardware merchant\nof Cando transacted business in the\ncity last week.\nAttorney T. W. Morrissey of Ed\nmore was a professional caller in\nthe city last week.\nFred Magnus, business man ef\nStarkweather, transacted business in\nthe city Saturday.\nN. P. Nelson and Peter Oram of the\nFisher farm transacted business in\nthe city Saturday.\nMr. and Mrs. Peter Dahl, of Crary,\nare the parents of a son born to.them\nat the General hospital.\nOluf Haggen, president of the bank\nat Lawton, attended to business mat\nters in the city Saturday.\nJohn H. Heimark, hardware mer\nchant of Warwick, was in the city\nlast week transacting business.\nE. C. Johnson, a prominent farmer\nfrom near Cando, was in the city\nMonday transacting business.\nMrs. J. J. Brawders, formerly of\nthis city but now of Warwick, visited\nin the city the fore part of the week.\nMr. and Mrs. 0. T. Geno had as\ntheir guests last week the Misses\nJosephine and Beatrice Bail of Penn.\nThe Business and Professional Wo\nmen's club are soliciting funds from\nthe business men of the city to pur\nchase a piano.\nCordwood $10.00 sawed $12 delivered\nposts 15c to 25c. Special prices on\nquantities in woods. W. B. Smith.\nPhone 295J c-l-12tf\nH. S. Pond, cashicr of the First\nNational bank of Crary, and John\nShand, also of Crary, attended to bus\niness in the city the latter part of\nthe week.\nMrs. John Heimark, of Warwick,\nreturned to her home Monday from\nthe Mercy hospital where she was a\npatient. She was accompanied by her\ninfant daughter.\nMrs. J. Dignan who has been visit\ning at the home of her sister, Mrs.\nW. J. Doyle and Mrs. L. Rainke at\nPenn, has returned to her home here\nafter an absence of several weeks.\nThe Calico dance by the G. A,. R.\nfor tomorrow evening at the Roller\nrink promises to draw a crowd from\nevery walk in life. Hundreds of\npersons are talking \"Calico Dance.\"\nJames McCormick, Sr., who fell on\nthe slippery sidewalk in front of the\npost office last week and sustained\nsevere injuries, is reported as resting\nmuch easier but still suffering some\nwhat.\nFOR SALE\u2014Pure bred Percheron\nStallion, Name\u2014Amasa, Register\nNo. 83384. Write or call. A. H.\nAnderson, Route No. 2, Edmore,\nN. Dakota. 2-9\nAmong those from Penn in the city\nMonday to attend the funeral of Mrs.\nCaroline Scnultz were Henry, Frank\nand Charles Gessner, Mr. and Mrs.\nHerman Kaeding, A. Mitchell and Miss\nMary Mitchell.\nR. A. Gibbens, farmer and livestock\nman of Cando, was in the city Monday\ntransactfiig business. Mr. Gibbens, it\nis said, is the only man in the Lake\nRegion that has had any considerable\nsuccess raising alfalfa.\nWhy Not A Dozen\nPhotographs?\nSend Us Your ^odalt Finishing\nPhone 189\nV\u00bbi\npr\nI 1\nCf'rw\nq*\nso\nify\nTfitl DEVILS\nValentines\u20143et them atSlorbjr A\nBerg's.\nr-\ncl-26\nA son was born Saturday, January\n2nd to Mr. and Mn. Clem Bsdmoad.\nDr. and Mn. W. C.FoUett are the\nproud parents of a son born to them\nat'^Mercy hospital SuiidSy.\nMr .and Mrt. Joe Lavalleof the\nopera house bl*tk have as their guest\nMr. Lavalee'g mother of Grand Forks\nMr. and Mrg, H. A. Swartx qX\nSchool avenne Ut\u00bb a&. theirguetf\ntheir son, Paid, of Starkweather,\nP. M. Pool,. Moclcmaa for the Ad\nvance-Rumley company, is attending\nan implement dealers convention in\nFargo.\nMrg. Harold Connolly entertained\nthe \"Live Wire Circle\" of the Presby\nterian church at her home Monday\nevening.\nCordwood $10.00 sawed $12 delivered\nposts 16c to '25c. Special prices on\nquantities in woods. W. B. Smith.\nPhone 29SJ c-l-12tf\nC. W. Greene, Blanding Fisher and\nA- V. Haig left Monday evening tor\nGrand Forks to attend a meeting of\nthe Grand Commandry.\nMrs. Curtis Anderson, formerly Miss\nJessie Monteith of this city, went to\nDoyon the first of the week to be a\nguest of Miss Neva Houser.\nVictor Wardrope, district juvenile\ncourt officer of Leeds, who has been\ncritically ill for .the past three weeks\nis reported as having recovered suf\nficiently to be about.\nMr .aqd Mrs. F. Martineau have\ntaken the C. Van Duyn flat in the\nMann annex. Mr. and Mrs. Van Duyn\nand son Harry have moved to Duluth\nwhere' they will make their home. Mr.\nMartineau is employed in\" the Ramsey\nDrug store.\n1\n'i\nPRICES ARE REACHING BOTTOM\nEXCEPTIONAL GROCERY VALUES\nFinest Quality Merchandise\nQuick 